00:00:46.830 --> 00:00:51.900
In 1884, two young
entrepreneurs,

00:00:51.900 --> 00:00:57.165
engineers by trade, decided to
pitch and propose a project--

00:00:57.165 --> 00:00:59.370
a technological project--

00:00:59.370 --> 00:01:02.100
that would change the world.

00:01:02.100 --> 00:01:05.340
Now, in 1884, given
how far back in history

00:01:05.340 --> 00:01:08.070
that is, the hot
technology of the day,

00:01:08.070 --> 00:01:12.390
we're not cloud computing or
mobile web application design.

00:01:12.390 --> 00:01:15.080
If you were a young person who
was ambitious, that had skills,

00:01:15.080 --> 00:01:16.770
were interested in
engineering and using

00:01:16.770 --> 00:01:19.050
technology to make
the human condition

00:01:19.050 --> 00:01:21.150
better, the field
you would be working

00:01:21.150 --> 00:01:24.360
in would be construction.

00:01:24.360 --> 00:01:26.970
Now, for us, we think of
construction as really boring.

00:01:26.970 --> 00:01:29.510
It's people with
hardhats and backhoes.

00:01:29.510 --> 00:01:33.030
But in 1884, this is the
rise of the industrial age.

00:01:33.030 --> 00:01:38.090
This is the rise of railroads
and telegraphy and telephones.

00:01:38.090 --> 00:01:40.500
It was also the rise
of industrialization

00:01:40.500 --> 00:01:41.850
for construction.

00:01:41.850 --> 00:01:45.150
At the time, in 1884, most
buildings in the world

00:01:45.150 --> 00:01:47.010
were not more than
a few stories high--

00:01:47.010 --> 00:01:49.620
five or six stories high--
because the technology

00:01:49.620 --> 00:01:52.050
at the time, the tools at
the time, the materials,

00:01:52.050 --> 00:01:53.130
were stone.

00:01:53.130 --> 00:01:55.680
And stone is not
reliable at scale.

00:01:55.680 --> 00:01:57.960
Generally speaking, it's
not affordable scale

00:01:57.960 --> 00:01:59.570
beyond a certain height.

00:01:59.570 --> 00:02:03.330
So these two young men in Paris,
France, Koechlin and Nouguier,

00:02:03.330 --> 00:02:07.030
they came up with a proposal for
how to use iron, wrought iron--

00:02:07.030 --> 00:02:09.330
which was a relatively
new tool and technology

00:02:09.330 --> 00:02:11.790
for the age-- to construct
what would be the largest

00:02:11.790 --> 00:02:13.204
building in the world.

00:02:13.204 --> 00:02:15.745
Now, as all of us would do if
we were in a similar situation,

00:02:15.745 --> 00:02:19.170
we had similar ambition, we had
an idea, we had a skill set,

00:02:19.170 --> 00:02:20.910
we would put together
a plan or proposal.

00:02:20.910 --> 00:02:22.800
We'd want to pitch
people on that idea.

00:02:22.800 --> 00:02:24.060
So that's what they did.

00:02:24.060 --> 00:02:26.190
And this is what their
pitch looked like.

00:02:26.190 --> 00:02:29.010
They drew, on paper, the
design for this building.

00:02:29.010 --> 00:02:32.820
And for those of you who have
ever been to Paris or France,

00:02:32.820 --> 00:02:35.405
this looks kind
of familiar, now.

00:02:35.405 --> 00:02:37.196
One thing they did in
this pitch-- and this

00:02:37.196 --> 00:02:38.700
is my first bit of
advice for you--

00:02:38.700 --> 00:02:42.060
is the grander the idea
is that you are pitching,

00:02:42.060 --> 00:02:44.490
the scarier it is for
people you are pitching to.

00:02:44.490 --> 00:02:46.500
You're asking them to
think in a bigger scale

00:02:46.500 --> 00:02:48.099
or take a larger amount of risk.

00:02:48.099 --> 00:02:50.640
So the first bit of advice I
can give you from my first story

00:02:50.640 --> 00:02:53.100
here is that whenever you're
pitching something grand,

00:02:53.100 --> 00:02:55.470
you need to find a way to
tell a story about it that

00:02:55.470 --> 00:02:57.530
ties it back to things
people already know.

00:02:57.530 --> 00:03:01.560
So in this little diagram
here, on the margins,

00:03:01.560 --> 00:03:04.855
they were smart
enough to put to scale

00:03:04.855 --> 00:03:06.840
six or seven of the
other tallest buildings

00:03:06.840 --> 00:03:08.840
in the world that are
already being constructed.

00:03:08.840 --> 00:03:11.020
So in the bottom, or
in the right corner,

00:03:11.020 --> 00:03:12.300
that's Notre-Dame.

00:03:12.300 --> 00:03:15.330
On top of it's the Statue of
Liberty, and on and on it goes.

00:03:15.330 --> 00:03:18.630
It so happens that one of
the good fortunes these two

00:03:18.630 --> 00:03:20.400
young men had is
they were employed,

00:03:20.400 --> 00:03:23.227
they worked for a
man named Eiffel.

00:03:23.227 --> 00:03:24.810
Eiffel, one of the
other contributions

00:03:24.810 --> 00:03:26.310
he had made before
the Eiffel Tower

00:03:26.310 --> 00:03:27.945
was working on the
Statue of Liberty.

00:03:27.945 --> 00:03:29.970
So I think they were
trying to say in here, hey,

00:03:29.970 --> 00:03:32.052
you could build something
seven times grander

00:03:32.052 --> 00:03:33.760
than this other thing
that you worked on.

00:03:33.760 --> 00:03:36.600
And it was much some highlight
in the quality of their pitch.

00:03:36.600 --> 00:03:40.530
The bad news is that
this pitch failed.

00:03:40.530 --> 00:03:44.400
Eiffel was like, eh, it's
tall, but it doesn't really

00:03:44.400 --> 00:03:45.660
do anything.

00:03:45.660 --> 00:03:48.030
It's kind of like
stunt technology.

00:03:48.030 --> 00:03:50.340
It's the tallest or the
fastest, but so what?

00:03:50.340 --> 00:03:51.750
It doesn't solve a problem.

00:03:51.750 --> 00:03:53.640
And also, from
Eiffel's point of view,

00:03:53.640 --> 00:03:56.040
it's not even really that
interesting to look at.

00:03:56.040 --> 00:03:57.540
So they rejected the pitch.

00:03:57.540 --> 00:03:59.340
But Eiffel, to his
credit, didn't tell them

00:03:59.340 --> 00:04:00.665
to stop working on the idea.

00:04:00.665 --> 00:04:02.790
He was like, you guys are
passion-- and by the way,

00:04:02.790 --> 00:04:03.706
I'm paraphrasing here.

00:04:03.706 --> 00:04:06.290
This is not literally
what Eiffel said.

00:04:06.290 --> 00:04:08.130
He's like, hey, guys,
I'm not into it.

00:04:08.130 --> 00:04:10.381
But you guys are passionate
about it, so keep working.

00:04:10.381 --> 00:04:10.921
And they did.

00:04:10.921 --> 00:04:12.340
They took his feedback to heart.

00:04:12.340 --> 00:04:14.880
They realized they needed
another element to the design

00:04:14.880 --> 00:04:16.380
to make it reach
Eiffel's standards.

00:04:16.380 --> 00:04:19.350
So they got a third architect
involved, a third engineer,

00:04:19.350 --> 00:04:20.640
named Sauvestre.

00:04:20.640 --> 00:04:23.850
If you think of the final
design of the Eiffel Tower,

00:04:23.850 --> 00:04:25.920
the bottom has those
beautiful arches.

00:04:25.920 --> 00:04:28.390
Sauvestre contributed
that design idea.

00:04:28.390 --> 00:04:30.240
So all the latticework,
and the fine

00:04:30.240 --> 00:04:33.690
patterns, and what looks
like an application

00:04:33.690 --> 00:04:35.310
of the golden ratio,
had the shapes

00:04:35.310 --> 00:04:37.920
of all these little
windows and this nice feel

00:04:37.920 --> 00:04:40.200
to them that draws
your eye in and makes

00:04:40.200 --> 00:04:41.760
you want to keep looking at it.

00:04:41.760 --> 00:04:43.990
That was Sauvestre's
contribution.

00:04:43.990 --> 00:04:45.900
They put together a
new pitch and proposal

00:04:45.900 --> 00:04:47.010
and they brought
that back to Eiffel.

00:04:47.010 --> 00:04:49.650
And of course, we all know,
this story has a happy ending.

00:04:49.650 --> 00:04:51.360
Yay, the Eiffel Tower exists.

00:04:51.360 --> 00:04:55.320
And it's probably the most
popular building in the world

00:04:55.320 --> 00:04:56.670
that people pay to go see.

00:04:56.670 --> 00:04:59.740
Certainly one of the most
popular buildings in history.

00:04:59.740 --> 00:05:01.006
And I tell you the story--

00:05:01.006 --> 00:05:01.755
I know where I am.

00:05:01.755 --> 00:05:03.012
I know I'm at Google.

00:05:03.012 --> 00:05:04.470
I know I'm talking
about technology

00:05:04.470 --> 00:05:05.910
that's more than 100 years old.

00:05:05.910 --> 00:05:08.200
But I'm here because
of a mission--

00:05:08.200 --> 00:05:10.710
one of my missions--
which is that we discount

00:05:10.710 --> 00:05:13.470
the value of history and what
we can apply from lessons

00:05:13.470 --> 00:05:15.428
from history, things that
happened in the past,

00:05:15.428 --> 00:05:18.300
to situations and problems
we're trying to solve today.

00:05:18.300 --> 00:05:20.010
And this book that
I just wrote called

00:05:20.010 --> 00:05:21.930
"The Dance of the
Possible," one of the things

00:05:21.930 --> 00:05:23.346
about it is a lot
of the stories I

00:05:23.346 --> 00:05:25.770
tell about how to solve
modern problems with working

00:05:25.770 --> 00:05:28.460
with ideas come from the past.

00:05:28.460 --> 00:05:31.380
Now, history is often
maligned in the tech sector.

00:05:31.380 --> 00:05:34.470
But part of what we know about
how all of our brains work

00:05:34.470 --> 00:05:36.240
is that whenever you
are making a decision

00:05:36.240 --> 00:05:38.573
or you're doing anything
actively today, in the present,

00:05:38.573 --> 00:05:41.590
in your life, guess what
is driving your thinking?

00:05:41.590 --> 00:05:42.430
History.

00:05:42.430 --> 00:05:44.170
Your history from last week,
your history from the meeting

00:05:44.170 --> 00:05:45.640
you had yesterday,
your history from what

00:05:45.640 --> 00:05:46.780
you learned in school.

00:05:46.780 --> 00:05:48.400
All of our decision
making is based

00:05:48.400 --> 00:05:51.690
on history, or our ability
to pull lessons out from what

00:05:51.690 --> 00:05:53.200
we've already experienced.

00:05:53.200 --> 00:05:56.980
So with that in mind, my first
lesson for you from the book

00:05:56.980 --> 00:06:00.220
is that all ideas are
made from other ideas.

00:06:00.220 --> 00:06:03.640
That all ideas, every idea,
every concept, every product,

00:06:03.640 --> 00:06:05.800
every methodology,
every philosophy,

00:06:05.800 --> 00:06:08.906
is comprised of other ideas
that came from somewhere else.

00:06:08.906 --> 00:06:11.030
So I'm going to ask you to
indulge me for a moment.

00:06:11.030 --> 00:06:15.454
I want you all to say this
sentence with me when I say so.

00:06:15.454 --> 00:06:16.870
OK, are you going
to do it for me?

00:06:16.870 --> 00:06:17.230
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:06:17.230 --> 00:06:17.680
SCOTT BERKUN: I think so.

00:06:17.680 --> 00:06:17.920
Good.

00:06:17.920 --> 00:06:18.430
OK.

00:06:18.430 --> 00:06:19.471
So on the count of three.

00:06:19.471 --> 00:06:20.658
One, two, three.

00:06:20.658 --> 00:06:23.590
AUDIENCE: All ideas are
made of other ideas.

00:06:23.590 --> 00:06:24.740
SCOTT BERKUN: Very good.

00:06:24.740 --> 00:06:26.700
Sound like a little
cult. This is good.

00:06:26.700 --> 00:06:29.511
We're forming a little
idea cult. Fantastic.

00:06:29.511 --> 00:06:31.510
Now, in the abstract, of
course, intellectually,

00:06:31.510 --> 00:06:32.860
we all know, yeah, of course.

00:06:32.860 --> 00:06:34.360
All ideas are made
from other ideas.

00:06:34.360 --> 00:06:36.730
Every mathematical formula
comes from other formulas.

00:06:36.730 --> 00:06:38.440
Every bit of
scientific progress is

00:06:38.440 --> 00:06:41.132
based on things that
were sorted out before.

00:06:41.132 --> 00:06:42.590
That's not really
what I mean here.

00:06:42.590 --> 00:06:44.740
What I mean here,
and the application

00:06:44.740 --> 00:06:47.110
of this that makes
it useful, is that we

00:06:47.110 --> 00:06:50.980
come across ideas, or
products, or notions

00:06:50.980 --> 00:06:53.230
that we have so
much respect for,

00:06:53.230 --> 00:06:54.624
that we forget this about them.

00:06:54.624 --> 00:06:56.540
And the Eiffel Tower's
an interesting example.

00:06:56.540 --> 00:06:58.930
How many of you have ever
seen before, that sketch?

00:06:58.930 --> 00:07:01.420
The original sketch
of the tower?

00:07:01.420 --> 00:07:02.080
No one.

00:07:02.080 --> 00:07:03.520
This is one of the most
significant buildings

00:07:03.520 --> 00:07:05.686
in the history of the world,
most popular buildings.

00:07:05.686 --> 00:07:07.450
But somehow, we
just forget that it

00:07:07.450 --> 00:07:09.080
had a back story and a history.

00:07:09.080 --> 00:07:11.480
That someone had to pitch
it and it got rejected.

00:07:11.480 --> 00:07:14.454
And they had the fortitude
and the grit to keep going.

00:07:14.454 --> 00:07:16.870
They had to incorporate and
collaborate with other people,

00:07:16.870 --> 00:07:18.880
that all of the stuff
contributed to this thing

00:07:18.880 --> 00:07:20.729
that we take for granted today.

00:07:20.729 --> 00:07:22.270
So the lesson here,
or the advice is,

00:07:22.270 --> 00:07:24.479
whenever you are stuck,
you're working on a problem--

00:07:24.479 --> 00:07:26.103
and it could be a
mathematical problem,

00:07:26.103 --> 00:07:27.670
it could be an
engineering problem--

00:07:27.670 --> 00:07:29.920
and you are stuck,
it probably means

00:07:29.920 --> 00:07:31.450
you're forgetting this lesson.

00:07:31.450 --> 00:07:34.395
Because when you're stuck, you
don't see any other way to go.

00:07:34.395 --> 00:07:36.020
But if you stop and
say, wait a second.

00:07:36.020 --> 00:07:37.103
I'm stuck on this problem.

00:07:37.103 --> 00:07:38.830
All ideas are made
from other ideas.

00:07:38.830 --> 00:07:41.730
What is this thing I am
working on comprised of?

00:07:41.730 --> 00:07:43.680
What are the component parts?

00:07:43.680 --> 00:07:46.340
Let me step back and go, OK,
has this algorithm, this thing,

00:07:46.340 --> 00:07:47.645
this bit of UI, OK.

00:07:47.645 --> 00:07:48.770
I'm going to take it apart.

00:07:48.770 --> 00:07:50.140
Now I have these six pieces.

00:07:50.140 --> 00:07:53.020
Well, what happens if I order
them in a different way.

00:07:53.020 --> 00:07:55.880
Or I take two of them and
I add some new thing to it.

00:07:55.880 --> 00:07:58.180
Now, all of a sudden,
you're not stuck anymore.

00:07:58.180 --> 00:07:59.680
Now, by combining
things, you're not

00:07:59.680 --> 00:08:01.220
guaranteed to have a good idea.

00:08:01.220 --> 00:08:03.212
But you will be back in
the state of progress

00:08:03.212 --> 00:08:05.170
where you are still
exploring and experimenting

00:08:05.170 --> 00:08:08.040
to learn more about the problem
that you were trying to solve.

00:08:08.040 --> 00:08:09.710
Now, before I
continue this lesson,

00:08:09.710 --> 00:08:10.840
my name is Scott Berkun.

00:08:10.840 --> 00:08:13.970
Nothing I am sharing with you
up here today is confidential.

00:08:13.970 --> 00:08:15.450
I am not a Google employee.

00:08:15.450 --> 00:08:17.950
So you are free to take
pictures, post on Twitter--

00:08:17.950 --> 00:08:19.090
that's my Twitter handle--

00:08:19.090 --> 00:08:20.926
all of my books and
anything else about me,

00:08:20.926 --> 00:08:22.300
including my email
address should

00:08:22.300 --> 00:08:24.383
you have a question that
we didn't have time for--

00:08:24.383 --> 00:08:26.764
Q&amp;A today-- just go
to scottberkun.com

00:08:26.764 --> 00:08:28.180
and everything is
there, including

00:08:28.180 --> 00:08:30.670
free chapters from the book.

00:08:30.670 --> 00:08:32.860
That said, let's get
back to all ideas being

00:08:32.860 --> 00:08:33.990
made of other ideas.

00:08:33.990 --> 00:08:35.101
So what you see here--

00:08:35.101 --> 00:08:37.600
so Eiffel's only known, really,
in most of the Western world

00:08:37.600 --> 00:08:40.030
for one product, for one thing.

00:08:40.030 --> 00:08:41.632
The tower, the Eiffel Tower.

00:08:41.632 --> 00:08:43.840
This is one of the first
buildings that Eiffel worked

00:08:43.840 --> 00:08:46.630
on, one of his first projects.

00:08:46.630 --> 00:08:52.250
And by comparison, it
is not so exciting.

00:08:52.250 --> 00:08:55.960
It's just a square box girder
bridge, and it's workman like,

00:08:55.960 --> 00:08:57.552
it functions, I
mean, it's reliable.

00:08:57.552 --> 00:08:59.260
It was built to have
trains go across it,

00:08:59.260 --> 00:09:01.420
which again, this was a
new technology of the day.

00:09:01.420 --> 00:09:03.234
A lot of people were
very scared of trains

00:09:03.234 --> 00:09:05.650
so building this really stable
and robust looking building

00:09:05.650 --> 00:09:07.660
was probably a good
design criteria.

00:09:07.660 --> 00:09:09.910
But there's nothing that
exciting about this building.

00:09:09.910 --> 00:09:11.680
This building doesn't
make it into history books

00:09:11.680 --> 00:09:12.640
unless you're
someone like me that

00:09:12.640 --> 00:09:15.476
wants to go back and find out
well, what did they do before.

00:09:15.476 --> 00:09:17.350
But he did incorporate
a whole bunch of ideas

00:09:17.350 --> 00:09:18.640
from engineering history.

00:09:18.640 --> 00:09:20.627
These grid systems for bridges.

00:09:20.627 --> 00:09:22.960
You can see wood bridges that
are made of the same truss

00:09:22.960 --> 00:09:27.130
structure, the square
structure repeated over a span.

00:09:27.130 --> 00:09:30.070
Later on in his career, this
was maybe five years or so

00:09:30.070 --> 00:09:32.590
before the Eiffel
Tower project, now you

00:09:32.590 --> 00:09:34.692
can see that his ability
to work with iron--

00:09:34.692 --> 00:09:36.650
with wrought iron, which
was the primary medium

00:09:36.650 --> 00:09:37.690
he liked to use--

00:09:37.690 --> 00:09:39.340
has gotten a lot more detailed.

00:09:39.340 --> 00:09:41.180
Some of what Eiffel became--

00:09:41.180 --> 00:09:43.030
at least in his
profession was famous for,

00:09:43.030 --> 00:09:45.370
was developing techniques
for using wrought iron

00:09:45.370 --> 00:09:47.320
more efficiently and
more effectively.

00:09:47.320 --> 00:09:48.986
So you look at this
design and it starts

00:09:48.986 --> 00:09:50.290
to have some magic to it.

00:09:50.290 --> 00:09:51.661
There's some appeal here.

00:09:51.661 --> 00:09:53.910
And a particular note to
this theme of all ideas being

00:09:53.910 --> 00:09:55.150
made of other ideas.

00:09:55.150 --> 00:09:58.990
The central element of
this bridge is an arch.

00:09:58.990 --> 00:10:02.050
An arch is one of the
oldest technologies

00:10:02.050 --> 00:10:05.170
for engineering construction
we have in the world.

00:10:05.170 --> 00:10:06.980
Hundreds and hundreds
of years old.

00:10:06.980 --> 00:10:10.570
So he took an old idea here, but
by combining it with something

00:10:10.570 --> 00:10:13.254
new he was working with, that
combination-- wrought iron,

00:10:13.254 --> 00:10:15.670
which had different properties
for strength and tension, ,

00:10:15.670 --> 00:10:18.430
didn't need as much material
to be just as strong--

00:10:18.430 --> 00:10:20.440
now it becomes transparent.

00:10:20.440 --> 00:10:22.330
You can see through
the arch, which

00:10:22.330 --> 00:10:24.560
gives it this dynamic effect.

00:10:24.560 --> 00:10:26.360
It's not just a
building anymore.

00:10:26.360 --> 00:10:28.151
It's a building that,
when you look at it--

00:10:28.151 --> 00:10:29.550
and to some
experience you have--

00:10:29.550 --> 00:10:31.615
in your brain, it's just
interesting to look at.

00:10:31.615 --> 00:10:32.740
It almost seems like magic.

00:10:32.740 --> 00:10:35.720
And you can imagine in
the 1850s and 1860s,

00:10:35.720 --> 00:10:37.690
1870s, around the
time this was built,

00:10:37.690 --> 00:10:41.530
how magical it must have been
to see this use of an old idea

00:10:41.530 --> 00:10:43.420
combine with something new.

00:10:43.420 --> 00:10:44.980
We also know that
he had influences,

00:10:44.980 --> 00:10:49.067
that Eiffel had thought earlier
on about building a huge tower.

00:10:49.067 --> 00:10:50.650
This is the Latting
Observatory, which

00:10:50.650 --> 00:10:54.029
was a World's Fair creation in
the 1950s in New York state.

00:10:54.029 --> 00:10:55.570
And this building,
when it was built,

00:10:55.570 --> 00:10:57.070
was the tallest building.

00:10:57.070 --> 00:11:00.127
But Eiffel saw this and had
the same complaint that he had

00:11:00.127 --> 00:11:01.960
to his two young engineers
when he saw this.

00:11:01.960 --> 00:11:04.120
He said, it's tall
and it's impressive,

00:11:04.120 --> 00:11:05.650
but it's basically
built to serve

00:11:05.650 --> 00:11:08.080
an abstract,
egotistical function.

00:11:08.080 --> 00:11:09.680
It's just the tallest building.

00:11:09.680 --> 00:11:11.346
And you could argue,
in a way, that when

00:11:11.346 --> 00:11:13.810
he saw this building in the
1850s, many years before he'd

00:11:13.810 --> 00:11:16.780
get pitched on the tower
idea, a problem space

00:11:16.780 --> 00:11:18.550
was created in his mind.

00:11:18.550 --> 00:11:20.956
And building a tall
tower was not enough.

00:11:20.956 --> 00:11:23.080
But there could be some
other kind of tall building

00:11:23.080 --> 00:11:24.910
that would satisfy
what he thought

00:11:24.910 --> 00:11:28.630
was the good use of a
technological innovation.

00:11:28.630 --> 00:11:34.390
A more local notion
or example for ideas

00:11:34.390 --> 00:11:37.210
being made of other ideas
is this famous drawing

00:11:37.210 --> 00:11:39.160
by da Vinci.

00:11:39.160 --> 00:11:40.792
Anyone know the name
of this drawing?

00:11:40.792 --> 00:11:41.875
AUDIENCE: "Vitruvian Man?"

00:11:41.875 --> 00:11:43.583
SCOTT BERKUN: "Vitruvian
Man," very good.

00:11:43.583 --> 00:11:45.970
So "Vitruvian Man," that's
the name of this drawing.

00:11:45.970 --> 00:11:47.886
And when we hear that,
"Vitruvian Man," we go,

00:11:47.886 --> 00:11:51.550
oh, "Vitruvian Man" must be
like the dude in the drawing.

00:11:51.550 --> 00:11:54.232
Maybe it was da Vinci's
neighbor, or the model,

00:11:54.232 --> 00:11:55.940
it's the name of the
model that he hired.

00:11:55.940 --> 00:11:56.680
No.

00:11:56.680 --> 00:11:59.650
Vitruvian is a reference
to Vitruvius and Vitruvius

00:11:59.650 --> 00:12:03.650
was a Roman architect who lived
a thousand years plus before da

00:12:03.650 --> 00:12:05.080
Vinci was even born.

00:12:05.080 --> 00:12:06.980
And Vitruvius wrote a book.

00:12:06.980 --> 00:12:09.529
That book is called "The
Ten Books on Architecture."

00:12:09.529 --> 00:12:11.320
Now, many of you are
engineers or designers

00:12:11.320 --> 00:12:12.550
or project managers.

00:12:12.550 --> 00:12:15.340
We like to think that art
industry, design patterns,

00:12:15.340 --> 00:12:18.590
that we concede to this
notion of putting together

00:12:18.590 --> 00:12:20.170
the blueprints for
how these patterns

00:12:20.170 --> 00:12:22.480
that repeat in our
work and sharing them.

00:12:22.480 --> 00:12:24.030
But Vitruvius wrote
this book called

00:12:24.030 --> 00:12:25.738
"The Ten Books on
Architecture," and it's

00:12:25.738 --> 00:12:28.694
the first design patterns
book in "The Western Canon."

00:12:28.694 --> 00:12:30.610
It's not about software
engineering of course,

00:12:30.610 --> 00:12:32.770
but it is about
actual engineering,

00:12:32.770 --> 00:12:34.360
actual architecture engineering.

00:12:34.360 --> 00:12:36.310
And da Vinci read a
passage in this book that

00:12:36.310 --> 00:12:39.015
was about scale proportion.

00:12:39.015 --> 00:12:40.390
And this goes back
to the Greeks.

00:12:40.390 --> 00:12:42.265
So this Roman guy, as
many of the Romans did,

00:12:42.265 --> 00:12:44.920
took ideas from the
Greeks, repurposed them.

00:12:44.920 --> 00:12:47.207
Like all the Greek
god names, the Romans

00:12:47.207 --> 00:12:49.540
took the same gods, basically,
just put a label on them.

00:12:49.540 --> 00:12:52.020
A lot of repurposing went
on in all those traditions.

00:12:52.020 --> 00:12:53.860
But specific to
this story, there's

00:12:53.860 --> 00:12:56.830
a passage in here that's
purely about the human form.

00:12:56.830 --> 00:12:59.620
And it's a passage that talks
about the size of your head

00:12:59.620 --> 00:13:01.870
should be about one eighth
of the size of your body,

00:13:01.870 --> 00:13:05.020
and the ratio between your
arm length to how long

00:13:05.020 --> 00:13:06.080
your legs are.

00:13:06.080 --> 00:13:08.810
And da Vinci read this passage
and was inspired enough to say,

00:13:08.810 --> 00:13:12.760
I want to make a drawing that
expresses this written idea.

00:13:12.760 --> 00:13:14.800
So that's where "Vitruvian
Man" comes from.

00:13:14.800 --> 00:13:16.420
But "Vitruvian
Man" is so popular

00:13:16.420 --> 00:13:18.450
because da Vinci is so
popular in our culture.

00:13:18.450 --> 00:13:20.320
This thing now is
a pattern, an idea,

00:13:20.320 --> 00:13:24.640
that's been reused and reused
again and again and again.

00:13:24.640 --> 00:13:27.160
Often without any knowledge
of where the idea came from

00:13:27.160 --> 00:13:28.680
or what the meaning of it was.

00:13:28.680 --> 00:13:31.090
And so now this idea, it's
been reused and recombined

00:13:31.090 --> 00:13:32.800
and recombined and recombined.

00:13:32.800 --> 00:13:34.690
And you see this
pattern everywhere.

00:13:34.690 --> 00:13:37.986
Now, often ideas get reused
in a way that's very ignorant.

00:13:37.986 --> 00:13:39.610
It's just this visual
thing that people

00:13:39.610 --> 00:13:40.735
go, oh, that's interesting.

00:13:40.735 --> 00:13:43.720
I know it's iconic I'm not going
to know why it became iconic,

00:13:43.720 --> 00:13:45.796
I'm just going to reuse it.

00:13:45.796 --> 00:13:47.170
But then you see
things like this

00:13:47.170 --> 00:13:50.230
where the show "Westworld"
has a version of "Vitruvian

00:13:50.230 --> 00:13:51.770
Man" in the logo.

00:13:51.770 --> 00:13:53.950
And now that you know some
of the history of what

00:13:53.950 --> 00:13:56.860
this drawing is from and what
it means, their use of this

00:13:56.860 --> 00:13:58.300
is actually very smart.

00:13:58.300 --> 00:14:00.190
They're talking about
reinventing man,

00:14:00.190 --> 00:14:01.900
reinventing the
idea of proportion,

00:14:01.900 --> 00:14:04.250
reinventing the
idea of perfection.

00:14:04.250 --> 00:14:07.000
So in these simple notions,
when you start peeling back

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:09.700
the layers of what an idea
is and you want to tear them

00:14:09.700 --> 00:14:12.040
apart, the landscape of
possibilities for what

00:14:12.040 --> 00:14:14.990
you can do now gets much wider.

00:14:14.990 --> 00:14:18.220
Now, to make this more practical
and more about products

00:14:18.220 --> 00:14:20.910
and creative thinking for
products, the advice for you

00:14:20.910 --> 00:14:22.330
that I have is this.

00:14:22.330 --> 00:14:25.030
That if you study the
history of a problem--

00:14:25.030 --> 00:14:26.210
the history of the problem.

00:14:26.210 --> 00:14:28.480
Not the technology,
but the problem,

00:14:28.480 --> 00:14:31.980
you'll find new ideas
for trying to solve it.

00:14:31.980 --> 00:14:34.830
The history of the
idea of the problem.

00:14:34.830 --> 00:14:39.810
An example that is close to
home, to drive this point home.

00:14:39.810 --> 00:14:42.900
Google, the first
major invention,

00:14:42.900 --> 00:14:44.460
back when the
company started, was

00:14:44.460 --> 00:14:47.460
PageRank, which I'm sure all
of you are very familiar with

00:14:47.460 --> 00:14:49.050
and can lecture me about.

00:14:49.050 --> 00:14:50.640
But what I know
about PageRank is

00:14:50.640 --> 00:14:55.410
that PageRank, the idea that you
can find the value of one page

00:14:55.410 --> 00:14:58.336
by examining how well
referenced it is by other pages

00:14:58.336 --> 00:14:59.710
and extending that
mathematically

00:14:59.710 --> 00:15:03.000
entirely through the network,
is an idea that was not invented

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:04.680
by the founders of Google.

00:15:04.680 --> 00:15:07.140
That was an idea that
was, in some sense,

00:15:07.140 --> 00:15:09.980
originated from research
papers themselves.

00:15:09.980 --> 00:15:13.140
Research papers, academic
papers, footnote at the bottom,

00:15:13.140 --> 00:15:15.491
all the people they are
referencing in their paper.

00:15:15.491 --> 00:15:17.490
And you can build an
index, and people did this.

00:15:17.490 --> 00:15:19.770
There are databases
and academic sources

00:15:19.770 --> 00:15:22.151
in colleges that
do the same thing.

00:15:22.151 --> 00:15:24.025
They see how many people
reference this paper

00:15:24.025 --> 00:15:26.960
and they build an index to find
the most referenced papers.

00:15:26.960 --> 00:15:29.490
So the very foundation of
the company that you work for

00:15:29.490 --> 00:15:31.080
was the recasting
of an idea that

00:15:31.080 --> 00:15:34.040
existed already and applied
to a different medium.

00:15:34.040 --> 00:15:36.960
Instead of research
papers, applied to the web.

00:15:36.960 --> 00:15:38.790
By understanding the
history of a problem,

00:15:38.790 --> 00:15:41.289
you will see different ways of
looking at the problem, which

00:15:41.289 --> 00:15:43.980
will invite new ideas and
points of view you would never

00:15:43.980 --> 00:15:47.280
find if you didn't go back
and study that history.

00:15:47.280 --> 00:15:50.820
Speaking of your competitors,
Amazon is a similar story.

00:15:50.820 --> 00:15:54.810
This is an ad from the early
1900s for Sears, Roebuck.

00:15:54.810 --> 00:15:56.550
And Sears, Roebuck,
for those of you

00:15:56.550 --> 00:16:00.960
who don't know, in the
industrial age, 1890s, 1900,

00:16:00.960 --> 00:16:03.480
they were the Amazon of America.

00:16:03.480 --> 00:16:05.550
They had a book,
this printed book,

00:16:05.550 --> 00:16:07.402
that contained every
product available

00:16:07.402 --> 00:16:09.360
that you could possibly
get through mail order.

00:16:09.360 --> 00:16:11.094
And mail order itself
was a new idea.

00:16:11.094 --> 00:16:12.510
If you read their
little tag line,

00:16:12.510 --> 00:16:14.850
it sounds a lot like
Amazon's ads today.

00:16:14.850 --> 00:16:16.890
We sell everything
by mail order only.

00:16:16.890 --> 00:16:20.760
Your money we promptly return if
you're not perfectly satisfied.

00:16:20.760 --> 00:16:24.230
This is basically playbook out
of Amazon's marketing campaign.

00:16:24.230 --> 00:16:26.670
And I tell you that
not because I'm

00:16:26.670 --> 00:16:29.040
trying to convince you to go
work at Amazon or anything,

00:16:29.040 --> 00:16:30.380
but if you compete
with Amazon, this

00:16:30.380 --> 00:16:32.100
is another competitive
strategy to use.

00:16:32.100 --> 00:16:35.280
Study the history
of the problem.

00:16:35.280 --> 00:16:36.990
Some ideas were
successful, but they

00:16:36.990 --> 00:16:40.190
were abandoned because the
person who ran with the idea

00:16:40.190 --> 00:16:43.140
ran out of money or that
industry, for a time,

00:16:43.140 --> 00:16:43.772
took a big hit.

00:16:43.772 --> 00:16:44.730
The whole industry did.

00:16:44.730 --> 00:16:48.302
So these good ideas are sitting
there for solving a problem

00:16:48.302 --> 00:16:49.010
but they're gone.

00:16:49.010 --> 00:16:50.130
They've been forgotten.

00:16:50.130 --> 00:16:53.140
You go back, have a better
view of the problem,

00:16:53.140 --> 00:16:54.530
and those ideas become yours.

00:16:54.530 --> 00:16:57.060
From a later catalog
in the 1940s,

00:16:57.060 --> 00:16:59.480
this is what basically
the conversion page--

00:16:59.480 --> 00:17:02.090
the equivalent of a conversion
web page-- the conversion page

00:17:02.090 --> 00:17:03.536
in that catalog looked like.

00:17:03.536 --> 00:17:05.119
And if you look at
this catalog design

00:17:05.119 --> 00:17:07.819
compared to conversion
pages on the web,

00:17:07.819 --> 00:17:10.310
there's a lot of smart
stuff going on here.

00:17:10.310 --> 00:17:12.540
You have anchoring,
price anchoring,

00:17:12.540 --> 00:17:14.630
using cognitive
science to help figure

00:17:14.630 --> 00:17:17.450
out how to convince people
to buy stuff, value leader.

00:17:17.450 --> 00:17:20.950
You have zoomed in versions
of the guitar strut.

00:17:20.950 --> 00:17:23.450
There's all kinds of ideas here
that you can go back and go,

00:17:23.450 --> 00:17:24.290
wait a second.

00:17:24.290 --> 00:17:27.947
There's things we've lost
in all of our progress.

00:17:27.947 --> 00:17:29.780
We've made things a lot
better in some ways,

00:17:29.780 --> 00:17:31.430
but there's ideas
here that could

00:17:31.430 --> 00:17:34.650
be reused and experimented
with and re-applied.

00:17:37.590 --> 00:17:40.157
My second lesson for you,
and I only have two more

00:17:40.157 --> 00:17:41.990
and then we'll open the
floor for questions.

00:17:41.990 --> 00:17:46.420
My second lesson for you
is that great ideas often

00:17:46.420 --> 00:17:48.200
look weird at first.

00:17:48.200 --> 00:17:54.270
If you are dealing
with a notion that

00:17:54.270 --> 00:17:57.310
is so much superior to
what you are familiar with,

00:17:57.310 --> 00:17:59.230
it's not going to
look normal to you.

00:17:59.230 --> 00:18:01.925
It's not going to make sense
in the worldview that you have.

00:18:01.925 --> 00:18:04.050
And when you go back and
look at the history of how

00:18:04.050 --> 00:18:05.716
we developed all these
technologies that

00:18:05.716 --> 00:18:06.810
we now take for granted--

00:18:06.810 --> 00:18:08.970
railroads being one,
the internet and the web

00:18:08.970 --> 00:18:11.215
being the second, mobile
devices being third.

00:18:11.215 --> 00:18:12.840
Go back and read
about the first couple

00:18:12.840 --> 00:18:15.297
of years of those devices
being products and people just

00:18:15.297 --> 00:18:17.130
looking at them, why
would you use that for?

00:18:17.130 --> 00:18:18.570
What would that do for me?

00:18:18.570 --> 00:18:21.780
That's the common response
even if the idea is sound.

00:18:21.780 --> 00:18:24.060
So to tie this back
home to the first story.

00:18:24.060 --> 00:18:27.510
When Eiffel proposed the tower
idea to the Parisian World's

00:18:27.510 --> 00:18:31.057
Fair committee, they accepted
it, which we all know.

00:18:31.057 --> 00:18:31.890
Two things happened.

00:18:31.890 --> 00:18:34.380
One, they told them we accept
it but only at half the budget

00:18:34.380 --> 00:18:34.921
you proposed.

00:18:37.360 --> 00:18:39.010
Half the budget.

00:18:39.010 --> 00:18:41.260
Eiffel was a businessman.

00:18:41.260 --> 00:18:43.270
We like to think of it
now as an arts project.

00:18:43.270 --> 00:18:44.770
This was purely done for
the beauty of the world.

00:18:44.770 --> 00:18:46.130
No, he was a businessman.

00:18:46.130 --> 00:18:47.095
So he saw this as
an opportunity.

00:18:47.095 --> 00:18:49.511
He's like, fine, I'll put up
the other half of the capital

00:18:49.511 --> 00:18:51.790
if I get ticket concessions.

00:18:51.790 --> 00:18:54.430
I get to sell
baguettes when people

00:18:54.430 --> 00:18:56.080
get inside the Eiffel Tower.

00:18:56.080 --> 00:18:57.440
I get all that money.

00:18:57.440 --> 00:19:00.010
So it's a business proposition
for him first and foremost.

00:19:00.010 --> 00:19:03.487
Second, and this is the
most shocking thing.

00:19:03.487 --> 00:19:04.320
Agree on the budget.

00:19:04.320 --> 00:19:05.220
They started working.

00:19:05.220 --> 00:19:08.490
They broke ground on
building the Eiffel Tower.

00:19:08.490 --> 00:19:12.720
300 or more of the leaders
of the cultural Zeitgeist

00:19:12.720 --> 00:19:15.235
in Paris, which is the
world leader at the time

00:19:15.235 --> 00:19:16.950
of the arts in world--

00:19:16.950 --> 00:19:20.490
poets, architects, musicians,
writers, politicians all

00:19:20.490 --> 00:19:22.920
got together in
outrage at how much

00:19:22.920 --> 00:19:25.950
they hated the idea
of the Eiffel Tower.

00:19:25.950 --> 00:19:27.106
They hated it.

00:19:27.106 --> 00:19:29.730
They thought it was a rejection
of all the norms of aesthetics.

00:19:29.730 --> 00:19:32.770
It was a rejection of the idea
of what technology should do.

00:19:32.770 --> 00:19:35.280
300 got together--
300 of these experts

00:19:35.280 --> 00:19:37.000
got together and wrote
an essay that they

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:39.990
made into a pamphlet-- it also
published in newspapers-- where

00:19:39.990 --> 00:19:42.150
they basically said, we
have to kill this project.

00:19:42.150 --> 00:19:44.826
I'm going to read a small
passage of this to you.

00:19:44.826 --> 00:19:46.200
"We writers,
painters, sculptors,

00:19:46.200 --> 00:19:49.320
architects protest with
all of our strength,

00:19:49.320 --> 00:19:51.060
with all our
indignation in the name

00:19:51.060 --> 00:19:55.340
of slighted French taste--"
which is a powerful force--

00:19:55.340 --> 00:19:58.080
"slighted French taste
against this tower."

00:19:58.080 --> 00:20:02.740
They also call it this mass of
iron gymnasium apparatus, which

00:20:02.740 --> 00:20:04.700
is pretty insulting.

00:20:04.700 --> 00:20:09.420
And all of us look at this and
go, these people were so wrong.

00:20:09.420 --> 00:20:12.337
How could they say this
about this great work?

00:20:12.337 --> 00:20:13.920
And that's how I
felt about this, too,

00:20:13.920 --> 00:20:15.360
when I first heard about this.

00:20:15.360 --> 00:20:19.950
But that's where this notion
of good ideas seeming weird

00:20:19.950 --> 00:20:22.530
is important, because we have
to put our heads back in time.

00:20:22.530 --> 00:20:23.730
We know too much now.

00:20:23.730 --> 00:20:25.950
Go back to 1885.

00:20:25.950 --> 00:20:28.170
Tallest buildings in
Paris, other than some

00:20:28.170 --> 00:20:31.310
of the churches, six stories
high, five stories high.

00:20:31.310 --> 00:20:34.002
You're walking around these
great promenades and parks,

00:20:34.002 --> 00:20:36.460
you're eating a baguette and
some cheese, having some wine.

00:20:36.460 --> 00:20:38.030
You're walking and
strolling along.

00:20:38.030 --> 00:20:42.630
And then, you turn a
corner and you see this.

00:20:42.630 --> 00:20:45.440
It does look kind of
monstrous in that context.

00:20:45.440 --> 00:20:47.070
It does look really foreign.

00:20:47.070 --> 00:20:50.269
Iron, wrought iron,
