00:22:22.144 --> 00:22:22.940
AUDIENCE: A what?

00:22:22.940 --> 00:22:24.710
SCOTT BERKUN: A human knee.

00:22:24.710 --> 00:22:25.340
Human knee.

00:22:25.340 --> 00:22:26.300
Part of your body.

00:22:26.300 --> 00:22:28.760
You're knee, middle of your leg.

00:22:28.760 --> 00:22:29.570
Prototype.

00:22:29.570 --> 00:22:31.850
OK, so I'll cut
to the chase here.

00:22:31.850 --> 00:22:34.070
This is a prototype that
was made by Doug Engelbart

00:22:34.070 --> 00:22:37.110
and Doug Engelbart is the
inventor of the mouse.

00:22:37.110 --> 00:22:41.150
And what he was thinking at
the time-- this is late 1860s--

00:22:41.150 --> 00:22:43.910
he's thinking of how do I make
human-computer interaction

00:22:43.910 --> 00:22:46.350
better?

00:22:46.350 --> 00:22:49.230
How do people interact with
computers and machines in 1865?

00:22:49.230 --> 00:22:51.690
Well, there's not
that many devices yet.

00:22:51.690 --> 00:22:53.251
There's cars.

00:22:53.251 --> 00:22:53.750
Sorry?

00:22:53.750 --> 00:22:54.670
AUDIENCE: 18 or 19?

00:22:54.670 --> 00:22:55.770
SCOTT BERKUN: 19.

00:22:55.770 --> 00:22:56.500
Yeah.

00:22:56.500 --> 00:22:57.940
That would be
impressive if he was

00:22:57.940 --> 00:23:00.320
working on the mouse in 1865.

00:23:00.320 --> 00:23:03.619
So in 1965, how did people
interact with machines?

00:23:03.619 --> 00:23:05.410
What's the interaction
models that we have?

00:23:05.410 --> 00:23:05.992
Cars.

00:23:05.992 --> 00:23:08.200
You drive with your car and
you drive with your hands

00:23:08.200 --> 00:23:10.380
you drive with your
feet, foot on the pedal.

00:23:10.380 --> 00:23:12.127
So that's one mode
that could be used.

00:23:12.127 --> 00:23:14.710
Also, sewing machines, which is
really the primary inspiration

00:23:14.710 --> 00:23:15.460
for this.

00:23:15.460 --> 00:23:16.880
Sewing machine, you
work with your hands,

00:23:16.880 --> 00:23:19.005
you have a foot on the
floor controlling something.

00:23:19.005 --> 00:23:21.220
So what he was thinking
here, his hypothesis

00:23:21.220 --> 00:23:25.690
in this experiment, was, why
not use this part of your body

00:23:25.690 --> 00:23:29.290
that goes unused to do xy,
pointing on the screen.

00:23:29.290 --> 00:23:31.885
Then, you have two hands free.

00:23:31.885 --> 00:23:33.760
It's actually kind of
a brilliant hypothesis.

00:23:33.760 --> 00:23:36.010
Even today, most
of our work, we're

00:23:36.010 --> 00:23:38.680
trying so hard to input all
this stuff into a computer.

00:23:38.680 --> 00:23:42.350
50% of our limbs don't
get used for that at all.

00:23:42.350 --> 00:23:44.410
This is fine if Wendy
wants to go quit Google

00:23:44.410 --> 00:23:48.280
and start up on extra
limb interface design.

00:23:48.280 --> 00:23:50.680
You're welcome to do it
because this is an old idea.

00:23:50.680 --> 00:23:52.152
But he was on the right track.

00:23:52.152 --> 00:23:54.610
He was thinking about how do
people interact with machines.

00:23:54.610 --> 00:23:57.820
Eventually, he developed
the model that we know,

00:23:57.820 --> 00:23:58.960
this direction.

00:23:58.960 --> 00:24:04.330
But even in 1970, 1971,
if he had shown this to us

00:24:04.330 --> 00:24:06.310
and we were alive then,
not from time travel,

00:24:06.310 --> 00:24:09.340
but we were alive then and
said this is the future,

00:24:09.340 --> 00:24:11.440
we'd be like, what
are you talking about?

00:24:11.440 --> 00:24:14.710
This is like a box on a string.

00:24:14.710 --> 00:24:18.070
The idea is expressing a whole
bunch of assumptions that are

00:24:18.070 --> 00:24:21.447
foreign and it will seem weird.

00:24:21.447 --> 00:24:23.530
The last piece of advice
here, to drive this home.

00:24:23.530 --> 00:24:25.738
I know a lot of this is
history and my promise to you

00:24:25.738 --> 00:24:27.790
was to apply history to today.

00:24:27.790 --> 00:24:29.230
So what this means
is, all of you

00:24:29.230 --> 00:24:30.820
are in meetings when
you're working on products,

00:24:30.820 --> 00:24:31.870
you're trying to
solve something,

00:24:31.870 --> 00:24:34.580
you're building something, where
you're discussing alternatives.

00:24:34.580 --> 00:24:36.966
There's proposal
a, proposal b, c.

00:24:36.966 --> 00:24:38.590
And maybe you have
some criteria you're

00:24:38.590 --> 00:24:41.716
using to vet them, like
user scenarios or the goals

00:24:41.716 --> 00:24:42.840
for your project, whatever.

00:24:42.840 --> 00:24:44.830
So you look at idea
a in this discussion

00:24:44.830 --> 00:24:46.570
and you say, oh, it's
good in these ways.

00:24:46.570 --> 00:24:47.480
Well, that's a good idea.

00:24:47.480 --> 00:24:49.030
We'll put it in
the good idea pile.

00:24:49.030 --> 00:24:50.025
Then, you go to
idea b and you're

00:24:50.025 --> 00:24:51.550
like, oh, we can
see already it's

00:24:51.550 --> 00:24:52.700
going to have these issues.

00:24:52.700 --> 00:24:54.158
That's going to go
in the bad pile.

00:24:54.158 --> 00:24:55.283
And you go through c and d.

00:24:55.283 --> 00:24:57.574
Every now and then, you're
going to have an idea that's

00:24:57.574 --> 00:24:59.650
proposed that you look at
it in these discussions

00:24:59.650 --> 00:25:03.017
and you go, that's,
that's really weird.

00:25:03.017 --> 00:25:05.350
And you turn to the person
who proposed it, you're like,

00:25:05.350 --> 00:25:06.570
can you explain this?

00:25:06.570 --> 00:25:08.770
And they'll probably go,
yeah that's a weird one.

00:25:08.770 --> 00:25:11.290
I feel like there's something
really to it that's good,

00:25:11.290 --> 00:25:13.037
but I haven't
figured it out yet.

00:25:13.037 --> 00:25:15.370
And the natural thing that
we do, since we're efficiency

00:25:15.370 --> 00:25:17.740
minded, we have
project deadlines,

00:25:17.740 --> 00:25:20.320
we take the weird ideas
and we throw them away

00:25:20.320 --> 00:25:22.180
with all the bad ideas.

00:25:22.180 --> 00:25:23.800
That's a mistake.

00:25:23.800 --> 00:25:28.420
The advice to you is to
keep weird ideas around.

00:25:28.420 --> 00:25:30.250
A weird idea means
you don't understand

00:25:30.250 --> 00:25:31.960
enough about the
problem or about

00:25:31.960 --> 00:25:35.210
the potential of the
idea to evaluate it.

00:25:35.210 --> 00:25:36.275
You can't judge it.

00:25:36.275 --> 00:25:37.900
And of course, if
you're on a deadline,

00:25:37.900 --> 00:25:40.390
you shouldn't ship this
idea you can't evaluate.

00:25:40.390 --> 00:25:42.830
But it also means there's
probably potential in it

00:25:42.830 --> 00:25:45.475
and if you study it more,
you pay attention to it,

00:25:45.475 --> 00:25:46.970
you come back to
it a week later,

00:25:46.970 --> 00:25:49.511
two weeks later, your point of
view is going to be different.

00:25:49.511 --> 00:25:51.500
You're going to ask
different questions of it.

00:25:51.500 --> 00:25:55.030
And you might find something
that leads to a discovery.

00:25:55.030 --> 00:25:57.385
Much of the history
of inventors, people

00:25:57.385 --> 00:25:59.920
who get credited with
inventing and discovering,

00:25:59.920 --> 00:26:01.332
a lot of what--

00:26:01.332 --> 00:26:03.040
I shouldn't say a lot
because this is not

00:26:03.040 --> 00:26:05.373
a guaranteed method, but there
are no guaranteed methods

00:26:05.373 --> 00:26:06.340
in the sort of work.

00:26:06.340 --> 00:26:08.710
But many of their
breakthroughs occurred

00:26:08.710 --> 00:26:11.110
because of things that
were weird to them,

00:26:11.110 --> 00:26:13.900
they kept around, and
kept experimenting on

00:26:13.900 --> 00:26:15.025
until they found its value.

00:26:15.025 --> 00:26:17.566
And the canonical example of
the story that's most well-known

00:26:17.566 --> 00:26:18.480
is the Post-it Note.

00:26:18.480 --> 00:26:20.110
The Post-it Note story.

00:26:20.110 --> 00:26:23.380
The cliche version is someone
had weak glue, accidentally

00:26:23.380 --> 00:26:26.065
discovered weak glue, and that's
how we got the Post-it Note.

00:26:26.065 --> 00:26:28.630
But that's a
shallow, empty story.

00:26:28.630 --> 00:26:31.090
The true part of the story,
which ties all this together,

00:26:31.090 --> 00:26:32.320
yes it's true.

00:26:32.320 --> 00:26:34.870
An engineer, at 3M,
was working on trying

00:26:34.870 --> 00:26:36.280
to make a strong glue.

00:26:36.280 --> 00:26:38.310
And by accident,
he made a weak one.

00:26:38.310 --> 00:26:39.880
But he didn't throw it away.

00:26:39.880 --> 00:26:43.227
He looked at it and was
like, this is weird.

00:26:43.227 --> 00:26:44.060
And he put it aside.

00:26:44.060 --> 00:26:45.726
Then, the next day
or a week later, he's

00:26:45.726 --> 00:26:48.265
like, what can I do with this?

00:26:48.265 --> 00:26:51.100
It can't solve the
intended problem,

00:26:51.100 --> 00:26:52.870
but maybe it's good
for something else.

00:26:52.870 --> 00:26:55.480
And he kept it around
for years, continually

00:26:55.480 --> 00:26:56.740
trying-- let me try it here.

00:26:56.740 --> 00:26:57.730
Let me try it there.

00:26:57.730 --> 00:26:59.200
He'd go to his
coworkers, go, hey,

00:26:59.200 --> 00:27:01.060
I had this stuff--
he didn't tell them

00:27:01.060 --> 00:27:02.500
what it was designed for.

00:27:02.500 --> 00:27:04.570
He just said, hey,
I got this stuff.

00:27:04.570 --> 00:27:06.100
What would you do with it?

00:27:06.100 --> 00:27:07.660
Sort of like an improv question.

00:27:07.660 --> 00:27:09.160
And he did all sorts
of experiments.

00:27:09.160 --> 00:27:11.697
Eventually, one of his coworkers
looked at that and said,

00:27:11.697 --> 00:27:12.280
you know what?

00:27:12.280 --> 00:27:13.720
Maybe I can use this.

00:27:13.720 --> 00:27:15.280
Because he had a problem.

00:27:15.280 --> 00:27:18.310
He sang in a choir and he wanted
to put notation on the choir

00:27:18.310 --> 00:27:19.860
sheets, the music sheets.

00:27:19.860 --> 00:27:21.870
So he said with that soft
glue, that weak glue,

00:27:21.870 --> 00:27:23.370
I could possibly
put something on it

00:27:23.370 --> 00:27:24.939
that I can easily take off.

00:27:24.939 --> 00:27:26.230
That's the breakthrough moment.

00:27:26.230 --> 00:27:27.280
What's often not said.

00:27:27.280 --> 00:27:30.220
It took years now of refining
that product and convincing

00:27:30.220 --> 00:27:31.810
people of its value
for the Post-it

00:27:31.810 --> 00:27:34.580
Note to become the product
that we know today.

00:27:34.580 --> 00:27:37.390
So in summation, any
story that you know of,

00:27:37.390 --> 00:27:39.220
any legendary creation--

00:27:39.220 --> 00:27:40.840
in the tech sector,
maybe you think

00:27:40.840 --> 00:27:42.790
the iPhone is one of the
greatest things ever made.

00:27:42.790 --> 00:27:44.440
Maybe you think PageRank
is a breakthrough

00:27:44.440 --> 00:27:45.730
in the history of technology.

00:27:45.730 --> 00:27:48.220
Whatever thing you
think of as perfect,

00:27:48.220 --> 00:27:51.340
being this masterpiece, they
all have a history where

00:27:51.340 --> 00:27:53.350
they started as experiments.

00:27:53.350 --> 00:27:56.590
And if you want to be someone
who makes masterpieces or makes

00:27:56.590 --> 00:27:58.380
great things, you
want to understand

00:27:58.380 --> 00:28:00.130
what that experimental
part of the process

00:28:00.130 --> 00:28:01.590
was like because
that's what you're

00:28:01.590 --> 00:28:03.964
going to have to emulate in
projects that you are working

00:28:03.964 --> 00:28:06.910
on and making something today.

00:28:06.910 --> 00:28:08.160
Now, my last lesson for you--

00:28:11.220 --> 00:28:14.100
purely about creative
thinking and how

00:28:14.100 --> 00:28:16.620
to develop that
skill in yourself--

00:28:16.620 --> 00:28:18.380
is that our minds are
naturally creative.

00:28:18.380 --> 00:28:21.430
It is wired into us, it's
part of our brain function.

00:28:21.430 --> 00:28:26.460
Anyone who is not in prison,
not in a psych ward, functions

00:28:26.460 --> 00:28:29.280
in a decent way, can
get to work and home,

00:28:29.280 --> 00:28:32.100
has a brain that is
functioning, and creativity

00:28:32.100 --> 00:28:33.420
is part of that brain function.

00:28:33.420 --> 00:28:35.460
And the best way to
illustrate this to you

00:28:35.460 --> 00:28:39.000
is a common scenario that occurs
to us in everyday life, which

00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:40.950
is losing your keys.

00:28:40.950 --> 00:28:43.282
So imagine tomorrow,
you wake up,

00:28:43.282 --> 00:28:45.740
you're getting ready for work--
actually, let's say Monday,

00:28:45.740 --> 00:28:47.760
unless some of you are
working on Saturday.

00:28:47.760 --> 00:28:49.860
Monday you wake up, you're
going to go to work.

00:28:49.860 --> 00:28:51.596
You do your normal
routine and you

00:28:51.596 --> 00:28:56.100
do your pre-airlock check of
like wallet, purse, phone,

00:28:56.100 --> 00:28:56.960
keys.

00:28:56.960 --> 00:28:59.251
And you reach for your keys
and the keys are not there.

00:28:59.251 --> 00:29:00.267
You go, OK.

00:29:00.267 --> 00:29:02.600
And your brain automatically
goes into first level mode.

00:29:02.600 --> 00:29:03.709
Well, where are my keys?

00:29:03.709 --> 00:29:06.000
Oh, normally when I come
home, I put them in the basket

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:06.660
by the front door.

00:29:06.660 --> 00:29:06.990
OK.

00:29:06.990 --> 00:29:08.610
So you go there,
look at the basket.

00:29:08.610 --> 00:29:10.380
And if they're not
there, you go, hmm.

00:29:10.380 --> 00:29:13.080
Brain goes to level two,
like fault tolerance,

00:29:13.080 --> 00:29:13.890
error checking.

00:29:13.890 --> 00:29:15.480
Maybe the keys fell
behind the basket,

00:29:15.480 --> 00:29:16.800
so you look behind the basket.

00:29:16.800 --> 00:29:18.240
Not there.

00:29:18.240 --> 00:29:21.660
Now your brain automatically
goes to level three.

00:29:21.660 --> 00:29:24.750
Creativity starts to
ensue without any ideation

00:29:24.750 --> 00:29:28.164
methods, any
brainstorming techniques.

00:29:28.164 --> 00:29:29.580
All of a sudden,
you start looking

00:29:29.580 --> 00:29:31.440
in your closet of
clothes that you have not

00:29:31.440 --> 00:29:33.330
worn in like a month.

00:29:33.330 --> 00:29:34.560
You just do it.

00:29:34.560 --> 00:29:38.070
You know it's a little
weird, but it could be.

00:29:38.070 --> 00:29:39.539
Somehow they could be there.

00:29:39.539 --> 00:29:41.580
When that doesn't work,
you go to the next level.

00:29:41.580 --> 00:29:43.860
You probably check
your pants again,

00:29:43.860 --> 00:29:46.580
somehow assuming that in the
time that you've been looking,

00:29:46.580 --> 00:29:49.125
they have rematerialized
where they should have been.

00:29:49.125 --> 00:29:50.250
Then, you go to level four.

00:29:50.250 --> 00:29:52.200
Maybe someone broke into
my house and stole them.

00:29:52.200 --> 00:29:53.520
But that doesn't make any sense,
of course, because they would

00:29:53.520 --> 00:29:54.510
have stolen other stuff, too.

00:29:54.510 --> 00:29:55.020
No.

00:29:55.020 --> 00:29:56.010
Maybe your cat took--

00:29:56.010 --> 00:29:58.770
your brain automatically
goes to these places.

00:29:58.770 --> 00:29:59.610
Biologically.

00:29:59.610 --> 00:30:02.230
You can't prevent it.

00:30:02.230 --> 00:30:03.810
The explanation is
this is the asset

00:30:03.810 --> 00:30:05.070
that we have as a species.

00:30:05.070 --> 00:30:08.100
We're not the strongest species,
we're not the fastest species.

00:30:08.100 --> 00:30:11.250
But our brains are good at
solving problems and inventing

00:30:11.250 --> 00:30:15.910
experiments and hypotheses
to try to solve problems.

00:30:15.910 --> 00:30:18.390
This situation is
an unpleasant one,

00:30:18.390 --> 00:30:20.306
so we're motivated by
a certain kind of fear.

00:30:20.306 --> 00:30:22.680
Our brains kick in in a way,
even though losing your keys

00:30:22.680 --> 00:30:25.255
is not the end of the world,
it does feel that way.

00:30:25.255 --> 00:30:27.600
Your amygdala, the
fight-or-flight response part

00:30:27.600 --> 00:30:30.180
of your brain is triggered
in these moments.

00:30:30.180 --> 00:30:31.680
And it's not
filtering out anymore.

00:30:31.680 --> 00:30:33.180
That's why these
ideas can bubble up

00:30:33.180 --> 00:30:36.720
from your subconscious and
you're willing to try them.

00:30:36.720 --> 00:30:39.300
Normally, in everyday life,
in ordinary situations,

00:30:39.300 --> 00:30:41.460
in work situations,
we have lots and lots

00:30:41.460 --> 00:30:43.420
of filters we are
automatically placing on what

00:30:43.420 --> 00:30:44.899
our subconscious can do.

00:30:44.899 --> 00:30:46.440
In workplaces, it's
often just simply

00:30:46.440 --> 00:30:47.929
about wanting to sound smart.

00:30:47.929 --> 00:30:49.470
If you have a filter,
you always want

00:30:49.470 --> 00:30:52.590
to sound smart in
conversations or you

00:30:52.590 --> 00:30:54.632
want to impress your boss
enough to get promoted.

00:30:54.632 --> 00:30:56.840
You're going to have a filter
on things that come out

00:30:56.840 --> 00:30:58.550
of your mind or come
out of your brain

00:30:58.550 --> 00:31:00.050
because you're
trying to be perfect.

00:31:00.050 --> 00:31:01.500
But as we've talked
about already,

00:31:01.500 --> 00:31:03.250
you have to be willing
to say weird things

00:31:03.250 --> 00:31:05.620
and experiment to find
the right way to go.

00:31:05.620 --> 00:31:07.140
So there is a mismatch here.

00:31:07.140 --> 00:31:09.730
Natural brain function allows
these things to happen,

00:31:09.730 --> 00:31:11.521
but there's all these
things and inhibitors

00:31:11.521 --> 00:31:14.230
we put on top of
it that prevent it.

00:31:14.230 --> 00:31:17.220
To sum this up in a neat little
phrase, when we are suitably

00:31:17.220 --> 00:31:21.090
motivated by a hard
problem, creativity ensues.

00:31:21.090 --> 00:31:22.320
It just happens.

00:31:22.320 --> 00:31:23.810
On its own.

00:31:23.810 --> 00:31:27.000
The two things that are
important, suitably motivated,

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:28.080
hard problem.

00:31:28.080 --> 00:31:31.285
If you're suitably motivated
to solve an easy problem,

00:31:31.285 --> 00:31:33.160
the creativity stuff
doesn't have to kick in.

00:31:33.160 --> 00:31:36.160
Losing your keys and if it's
the first place you look, done.

00:31:36.160 --> 00:31:37.510
Our brains are lazy.

00:31:37.510 --> 00:31:39.620
Why invent all these
weird scenarios?

00:31:39.620 --> 00:31:42.490
Suitably motivated
by a hard problem.

00:31:42.490 --> 00:31:44.440
Now, to wrap up, I
have three pieces

00:31:44.440 --> 00:31:46.972
of specific advice
about creative thinking.

00:31:46.972 --> 00:31:48.930
This will be the last
set of points that I make

00:31:48.930 --> 00:31:50.880
and then I'll open the
