00:31:52.360 --> 00:31:54.730
of what we talked about before.

00:31:54.730 --> 00:31:58.370
Everything I showed you,
Eiffel's work, Doug Engelbart,

00:31:58.370 --> 00:32:02.440
da Vinci, when you look at
it from a broad perspective,

00:32:02.440 --> 00:32:03.580
what were they all doing?

00:32:03.580 --> 00:32:05.350
They were all working.

00:32:05.350 --> 00:32:06.880
They had notions for things.

00:32:06.880 --> 00:32:10.510
da Vinci was inspired
by the passage he read.

00:32:10.510 --> 00:32:11.510
There was an idea there.

00:32:11.510 --> 00:32:12.490
But he got to work,
he said I want

00:32:12.490 --> 00:32:14.781
to express [INAUDIBLE] I'm
going to try this thing out.

00:32:14.781 --> 00:32:17.052
The two young engineers
had an idea, a concept.

00:32:17.052 --> 00:32:19.510
They didn't just let it sit as
a concept, they got to work.

00:32:19.510 --> 00:32:22.270
They made a sketch,
they made a prototype.

00:32:22.270 --> 00:32:25.460
Creativity is best thought of
in the smaller form of the word.

00:32:25.460 --> 00:32:25.960
Create.

00:32:25.960 --> 00:32:29.320
It's a verb, it's
something that you do.

00:32:29.320 --> 00:32:31.180
In the process of
making things, that's

00:32:31.180 --> 00:32:32.920
where creativity
can be expressed.

00:32:32.920 --> 00:32:35.640
It's not some abstract
thing, some abstract skill

00:32:35.640 --> 00:32:36.920
you develop on its own.

00:32:36.920 --> 00:32:38.980
It has to be done through
the process of work.

00:32:38.980 --> 00:32:41.140
Second, false constraints.

00:32:41.140 --> 00:32:43.000
So what I said to
you just a minute

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:44.535
ago about keys
and the inhibitors

00:32:44.535 --> 00:32:47.410
that we put upon our brain,
our natural creative brain

00:32:47.410 --> 00:32:48.420
function.

00:32:48.420 --> 00:32:51.101
There are false constraints
that we put upon our thinking.

