00:34:04.176 --> 00:34:06.050
There's all these
conventions and constraints

00:34:06.050 --> 00:34:07.633
that we naturally
apply to situations.

00:34:07.633 --> 00:34:10.670
That's how society
and civilization work.

00:34:10.670 --> 00:34:13.037
But we're talking
about creativity here.

00:34:13.037 --> 00:34:14.620
The exercise here
that you're trying--

00:34:14.620 --> 00:34:17.600
the message they're trying to
get across in this puzzle is

00:34:17.600 --> 00:34:20.630
if you work through a list of
all the constraints you think

00:34:20.630 --> 00:34:21.710
are true--

00:34:21.710 --> 00:34:23.460
let's say you come up
with seven of them--

00:34:23.460 --> 00:34:26.480
and it turns out one of
those constraints is false,

00:34:26.480 --> 00:34:29.540
that's a window of
possibilities now that opens up.

00:34:29.540 --> 00:34:31.400
And that's where ideas are.

00:34:31.400 --> 00:34:33.830
It's not this generative
thing, it's actually reductive.

00:34:33.830 --> 00:34:36.120
Oh, if I don't have to
worry about budget for this,

00:34:36.120 --> 00:34:36.620
OK, now--

00:34:36.620 --> 00:34:38.619
If I don't have to worry
about schedule for this

00:34:38.619 --> 00:34:40.190
or I have an extra
week, I assumed

00:34:40.190 --> 00:34:41.315
this had to be done Friday.

00:34:41.315 --> 00:34:42.440
Oh, it's Monday?

00:34:42.440 --> 00:34:43.670
Possibilities open up.

00:34:43.670 --> 00:34:45.679
So it's a logical exercise.

00:34:45.679 --> 00:34:47.659
Any time you're
stuck on a problem,

00:34:47.659 --> 00:34:50.270
make a list of the constraints
that you are assuming are true.

00:34:50.270 --> 00:34:52.103
Show it to a coworker,
show it to your boss.

00:34:52.103 --> 00:34:53.300
They'll go, really?

00:34:53.300 --> 00:34:54.510
That's not the goal.

00:34:54.510 --> 00:34:55.730
The goal-- you go, ah.

00:34:55.730 --> 00:34:57.740
Now, the window of
possibilities opens up.

00:34:57.740 --> 00:35:01.770
For fun, there are many other
possible solutions for this.

00:35:01.770 --> 00:35:04.020
Infinite in fact.

00:35:04.020 --> 00:35:06.020
You could do it in three
lines if you go really

00:35:06.020 --> 00:35:07.560
outside the box.

00:35:07.560 --> 00:35:09.890
You can do it in one
line, if it's a fat line.

00:35:09.890 --> 00:35:12.020
No one told you the
size of the line.

00:35:12.020 --> 00:35:13.670
You could do it
in one line if it

00:35:13.670 --> 00:35:16.850
goes all the way around the
world and goes back around.

00:35:16.850 --> 00:35:19.200
The more absurd you're
willing to get, the more silly

00:35:19.200 --> 00:35:21.630
you're willing to get, the more
solutions you can come up with.

00:35:21.630 --> 00:35:24.129
But there should be an infinite
number of solutions to this.

00:35:24.129 --> 00:35:26.181
So an exercise for you
could be see if you

00:35:26.181 --> 00:35:28.370
can come up with more of them.

00:35:28.370 --> 00:35:32.157
Then, my last note for
you is about self-respect.

00:35:32.157 --> 00:35:33.740
So I told you all
that your brains are

00:35:33.740 --> 00:35:35.610
wired by design to be creative.

00:35:35.610 --> 00:35:37.280
That stuff is in you.

00:35:37.280 --> 00:35:39.834
Society, and as we get older,
and we try to get good grades,

00:35:39.834 --> 00:35:41.750
and try to get good jobs,
and good performance

00:35:41.750 --> 00:35:42.925
reviews, constraints.

00:35:42.925 --> 00:35:44.870
We pile constraints
on and we forget

00:35:44.870 --> 00:35:46.580
that natural part of ourselves.

00:35:46.580 --> 00:35:50.900
So the best single habit
to learn and practice

00:35:50.900 --> 00:35:53.690
is to have a place for
yourself where your ideas can

00:35:53.690 --> 00:35:55.682
go that no one will see.

00:35:55.682 --> 00:35:57.140
And the most obvious
way to do this

00:35:57.140 --> 00:35:58.790
is a journal, some
kind of journal.

00:35:58.790 --> 00:36:00.890
A book, it could
be a Google Doc.

00:36:00.890 --> 00:36:02.587
It could be anything
where you can

00:36:02.587 --> 00:36:04.420
put stuff that's in
your brain, you're like,

00:36:04.420 --> 00:36:06.544
that's an interesting idea,
and you can put it down

00:36:06.544 --> 00:36:08.016
and no one else is
going to see it.

00:36:08.016 --> 00:36:09.740
You are training
your subconscious

00:36:09.740 --> 00:36:11.039
to start talking to you again.

00:36:11.039 --> 00:36:13.580
And you're going to listen more
carefully now because there's

00:36:13.580 --> 00:36:15.140
a place for it to go.

00:36:15.140 --> 00:36:17.790
Even more importantly,
our memories are terrible.

00:36:17.790 --> 00:36:19.130
We have terrible memories.

00:36:19.130 --> 00:36:22.520
Once you put something in the
world, there's some chance--

00:36:22.520 --> 00:36:24.222
even if it's a small chance--

00:36:24.222 --> 00:36:26.180
that you can come back
to it and go, oh, right.

00:36:26.180 --> 00:36:27.796
I can use this in
my next project.

00:36:27.796 --> 00:36:30.170
But if it just goes through
your mind and out your brain,

00:36:30.170 --> 00:36:31.580
you'll never see it again.

00:36:31.580 --> 00:36:34.820
So most artists,
scientists, researchers

00:36:34.820 --> 00:36:36.720
keep some kind of journal.

00:36:36.720 --> 00:36:38.700
Even people who work
on curing cancer.

00:36:38.700 --> 00:36:40.010
They have lab notes.

00:36:40.010 --> 00:36:42.800
They put down their observations
and thoughts habitually

00:36:42.800 --> 00:36:45.230
so that they can come back
later and go, oh, right.

00:36:45.230 --> 00:36:47.105
I forgot about this,
and I thought about this

00:36:47.105 --> 00:36:47.690
four days ago.

00:36:47.690 --> 00:36:49.520
Put these two pieces
together, boom.

00:36:49.520 --> 00:36:52.190
I got something new.

00:36:52.190 --> 00:36:53.090
So keeping a journal.

00:36:56.227 --> 00:36:57.810
There's an element
