00:39:51.019 --> 00:39:52.810
Because when you go to
a field or a subject

00:39:52.810 --> 00:39:55.840
you know nothing about,
you don't have any pressure

00:39:55.840 --> 00:39:57.460
of sounding stupid.

00:39:57.460 --> 00:40:01.360
So a lot of people who want
to be more inventive and they

00:40:01.360 --> 00:40:02.844
work in the tech
sector, they try

00:40:02.844 --> 00:40:04.510
to find another tech
sector event that's

00:40:04.510 --> 00:40:05.384
more about invention.

00:40:05.384 --> 00:40:06.670
And I'm like, no.

00:40:06.670 --> 00:40:10.900
Go to an event that's about
a different field, preferably

00:40:10.900 --> 00:40:13.399
one where they are inventing
things, but not technological.

00:40:13.399 --> 00:40:15.190
And you will hear things
and observe things

00:40:15.190 --> 00:40:16.390
that will make you curious.

00:40:16.390 --> 00:40:17.990
And that curiosity,
you'll ask questions.

00:40:17.990 --> 00:40:19.573
And then asking those
questions you'll

00:40:19.573 --> 00:40:22.720
say, well, when I'm
building something,

00:40:22.720 --> 00:40:23.660
this is how we do it.

00:40:23.660 --> 00:40:25.637
How do you do this?

00:40:25.637 --> 00:40:27.220
And those kinds of
conversations, now,

00:40:27.220 --> 00:40:29.674
where you're comparing
across fields--

00:40:29.674 --> 00:40:31.090
I guess what I'm
trying to say is,

00:40:31.090 --> 00:40:35.590
there's probably someone
just like you in the plumbing

00:40:35.590 --> 00:40:40.070
industry or the-- you
mentioned games or like the--

00:40:40.070 --> 00:40:42.400
someone who makes board
games for a living or someone

00:40:42.400 --> 00:40:45.255
who's like a medical engineer.

00:40:45.255 --> 00:40:46.630
The closer you
can get to someone

00:40:46.630 --> 00:40:48.460
who is a parallel to you
but has the completely

00:40:48.460 --> 00:40:50.543
different background, those
kinds of conversations

00:40:50.543 --> 00:40:51.802
are the powerful ones.

00:40:51.802 --> 00:40:53.260
It's hard to find
those connections

00:40:53.260 --> 00:40:55.670
because you have to reach out
across your comfort level.

00:40:55.670 --> 00:40:59.590
But again, it's about
going into the unknown.

00:40:59.590 --> 00:41:00.849
Next question?

00:41:00.849 --> 00:41:02.890
AUDIENCE: So the computers
that we're using today

00:41:02.890 --> 00:41:05.970
are based on technology that was
invented in the 20th century.

00:41:05.970 --> 00:41:08.980
But in the 19th century, we
had Boole, who did the math,

00:41:08.980 --> 00:41:11.890
and Babbage made the the engine.

00:41:11.890 --> 00:41:12.960
What were those based on?

00:41:12.960 --> 00:41:16.480
What was previous
technology that

00:41:16.480 --> 00:41:18.809
was basically the forerunner
of those computers?

00:41:18.809 --> 00:41:19.600
SCOTT BERKUN: Sure.

00:41:19.600 --> 00:41:20.683
So that's a good question.

00:41:20.683 --> 00:41:22.160
I don't know about Boole.

00:41:22.160 --> 00:41:25.030
Boole was a mathematician
so he would probably

00:41:25.030 --> 00:41:29.217
say there was mathematical
theories and hypotheses he

00:41:29.217 --> 00:41:29.800
was following.

00:41:29.800 --> 00:41:32.830
Babbage, I'm sure was
influenced by clock making.

00:41:32.830 --> 00:41:34.240
For sure.

00:41:34.240 --> 00:41:37.450
At that time, the most
sophisticated engineering

00:41:37.450 --> 00:41:40.000
for mechanical gear
work were clock makers.

00:41:40.000 --> 00:41:43.326
And there's a long history and
tradition of that design work

00:41:43.326 --> 00:41:44.200
and engineering work.

00:41:44.200 --> 00:41:46.630
I have to believe that
when he started his work,

00:41:46.630 --> 00:41:48.437
he looked at clocks first.

00:41:48.437 --> 00:41:50.020
And the gearing, I
mean, just the fact

00:41:50.020 --> 00:41:51.880
of how do you make intricate
gearing and that kind

00:41:51.880 --> 00:41:52.660
of sophistication?

00:41:52.660 --> 00:41:56.080
Where would you look if you
were alive at that time?

00:41:56.080 --> 00:41:58.080
It had to be clockwork.

00:41:58.080 --> 00:42:00.612
For sure.

00:42:00.612 --> 00:42:01.320
Another question?

00:42:05.139 --> 00:42:07.180
AUDIENCE: Well, I was
hoping to have a little bit

00:42:07.180 --> 00:42:08.160
more time to think about it.

00:42:08.160 --> 00:42:08.868
SCOTT BERKUN: OK.

00:42:08.868 --> 00:42:11.470
Is there an interstitial
question someone

00:42:11.470 --> 00:42:13.952
can ask to save your coworker?

00:42:13.952 --> 00:42:14.785
You have a question.

00:42:14.785 --> 00:42:16.492
AUDIENCE: So about
creativity, is it

00:42:16.492 --> 00:42:17.700
something that you can force?

00:42:17.700 --> 00:42:19.930
Or are you saying maybe
to carve out time daily

00:42:19.930 --> 00:42:24.970
to be creative, or
have ideas, or journal?

00:42:24.970 --> 00:42:27.650
SCOTT BERKUN: I think
that the answer is both.

00:42:27.650 --> 00:42:29.440
It's an unfair answer.

00:42:29.440 --> 00:42:30.400
You can force it.

00:42:30.400 --> 00:42:32.710
The key example is a
good example of that.

00:42:32.710 --> 00:42:35.127
If you're really desperate,
you're going to be--

00:42:35.127 --> 00:42:36.710
again, without even
thinking about it,

00:42:36.710 --> 00:42:39.722
without trying to summon your
creative gods or anything,

00:42:39.722 --> 00:42:41.680
those ideas just start
going through your mind.

00:42:41.680 --> 00:42:45.280
So there is something to be
said for putting yourself

00:42:45.280 --> 00:42:47.230
in situations that
will test you.

00:42:47.230 --> 00:42:51.176
But the habits of it,
the habits of creation,

00:42:51.176 --> 00:42:53.300
are something that you
really need to do every day.

00:42:53.300 --> 00:42:54.520
That's what a journal is for.

00:42:54.520 --> 00:42:55.935
I mean, to drive the
journal example--

00:42:55.935 --> 00:42:57.730
to tie his question
to the journal thing

00:42:57.730 --> 00:42:58.750
I was trying to say.

00:42:58.750 --> 00:43:02.080
If I had this habit for myself
of I think of some notion

00:43:02.080 --> 00:43:03.190
and I put it down.

00:43:03.190 --> 00:43:04.960
I think of some notion
and I put it down.

00:43:04.960 --> 00:43:07.210
And I come back a week later
and I look at that notion

00:43:07.210 --> 00:43:09.160
and I go, ah, and
I expand it out.

00:43:09.160 --> 00:43:12.280
My own confidence in my
ability to come up with ideas

00:43:12.280 --> 00:43:14.290
and to talk to my
own subconscious

00:43:14.290 --> 00:43:16.531
improves and improves over time.

00:43:16.531 --> 00:43:17.530
So that's like a muscle.

00:43:17.530 --> 00:43:19.382
It's like practicing
anything else.

00:43:19.382 --> 00:43:20.840
But there are some
situations where

00:43:20.840 --> 00:43:23.423
you're going get-- some people
feel most creative when they're

00:43:23.423 --> 00:43:25.870
at a deadline or when they
are working on a high stress

00:43:25.870 --> 00:43:27.667
project, for some people.

00:43:27.667 --> 00:43:29.500
There's no universal
answer to these things,

00:43:29.500 --> 00:43:31.450
of course, because
we're all different.

00:43:31.450 --> 00:43:33.366
And that's part of why
I hate all these recipe

00:43:33.366 --> 00:43:36.460
books, the seven killer
steps, the six secret silver

00:43:36.460 --> 00:43:38.680
bullets, because
the goal here is

00:43:38.680 --> 00:43:41.140
for you to apply
your unique worldview

00:43:41.140 --> 00:43:42.352
and experiences to a problem.

00:43:42.352 --> 00:43:44.560
That's what you're trying
to be when you're creative.

00:43:44.560 --> 00:43:46.101
So sort of like the
joke where I made

00:43:46.101 --> 00:43:49.350
you all say at the same time
all ideas come from other ideas.

00:43:49.350 --> 00:43:51.551
There can't be any
universal way to do this.

00:43:51.551 --> 00:43:53.050
Part of what you
have to do is to be

00:43:53.050 --> 00:43:56.020
more self aware of your
own habits and tendencies.

00:43:56.020 --> 00:43:58.610
And a lot of people are
really afraid of journaling

00:43:58.610 --> 00:44:01.510
because they're afraid of what
thing they will put in there.

00:44:01.510 --> 00:44:04.150
But if you're afraid
of your own ideas then

00:44:04.150 --> 00:44:06.770
you probably need
to seek therapy.

00:44:06.770 --> 00:44:08.360
No, therapy's a good thing.

00:44:08.360 --> 00:44:09.460
It's not a pejorative.

00:44:09.460 --> 00:44:10.954
But if really that's
the inhibitor,

00:44:10.954 --> 00:44:13.120
it's got nothing to do with
the world or your brain.

00:44:13.120 --> 00:44:15.430
It's your own psychology
and your fear of what

00:44:15.430 --> 00:44:16.629
your brain may come up with.

00:44:16.629 --> 00:44:18.170
You can't be afraid
of that any more.

00:44:18.170 --> 00:44:19.930
That's why journaling
helps so much.

00:44:19.930 --> 00:44:22.540
You get comfortable and
familiar with the weird things

00:44:22.540 --> 00:44:24.760
your subconscious
tends to suggest.

00:44:24.760 --> 00:44:26.392
Are you ready for
your question now?

00:44:26.392 --> 00:44:27.870
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I think so.

00:44:27.870 --> 00:44:30.190
So my question is
at the other end

00:44:30.190 --> 00:44:34.050
of the spectrum, where you
constantly think of, oh, maybe

00:44:34.050 --> 00:44:34.760
I can do this.

00:44:34.760 --> 00:44:37.380
And well, before you're about
to do that you're like, oh, what

00:44:37.380 --> 00:44:38.360
about this other idea.

00:44:38.360 --> 00:44:39.340
SCOTT BERKUN: Ah, OK.

00:44:39.340 --> 00:44:42.940
AUDIENCE: And you have this
infinite loop about new ideas.

00:44:42.940 --> 00:44:43.940
Any suggestion for that?

00:44:43.940 --> 00:44:45.356
SCOTT BERKUN: I
have a suggestion,

00:44:45.356 --> 00:44:46.450
but it's similar to--

00:44:46.450 --> 00:44:50.200
let's take this example and
put it into everyday terms.

00:44:50.200 --> 00:44:53.110
Let's say I was single and
I go on a first date and I

00:44:53.110 --> 00:44:54.220
kind of like that person.

00:44:54.220 --> 00:44:54.800
Then, I go on another date.

00:44:54.800 --> 00:44:56.280
I kind of like that person.

00:44:56.280 --> 00:44:57.940
And I never-- what
would you say?

00:44:57.940 --> 00:44:59.012
I never?

00:44:59.012 --> 00:44:59.720
AUDIENCE: Commit.

00:44:59.720 --> 00:45:00.595
SCOTT BERKUN: Commit.

00:45:00.595 --> 00:45:01.810
Never commit.

00:45:01.810 --> 00:45:03.680
If you never commit
to something,

00:45:03.680 --> 00:45:09.230
that means that you maybe don't
really want to do this thing.

00:45:09.230 --> 00:45:11.360
That all those ideas
are good, but maybe you

00:45:11.360 --> 00:45:14.690
find it more fun to just play
with the idea in your mind.

00:45:14.690 --> 00:45:16.190
For a lot of
people, that's true.

00:45:16.190 --> 00:45:17.787
Because as I said,
creativity is work.

00:45:17.787 --> 00:45:19.370
Once you say, I want
to write a novel,

00:45:19.370 --> 00:45:21.027
I want to start a company.

00:45:21.027 --> 00:45:22.610
Hey, it's an epiphany,
it feels great.

00:45:22.610 --> 00:45:23.990
Over dinner and wine
with your friends,

00:45:23.990 --> 00:45:24.695
I'm going to start a company.

00:45:24.695 --> 00:45:25.760
They go, yeah.

00:45:25.760 --> 00:45:29.450
Then, the next day, you're
like, oh, I got to call people,

00:45:29.450 --> 00:45:31.220
I got to write
documents, I got to--

00:45:31.220 --> 00:45:33.046
this doesn't feel
so creative anymore.

00:45:33.046 --> 00:45:33.920
This feels like work.

00:45:33.920 --> 00:45:34.962
Maybe I'm doing it wrong.

00:45:34.962 --> 00:45:36.503
Go to dinner with
your friends again.

00:45:36.503 --> 00:45:37.970
Hey, I'm going to make a movie.

00:45:37.970 --> 00:45:40.610
And you go through the
same loop of confusing

00:45:40.610 --> 00:45:43.550
the fun of coming up with
the idea with the reality

00:45:43.550 --> 00:45:46.530
of the work of actually
putting that idea in the world.

00:45:46.530 --> 00:45:49.160
So I would say to you
that it doesn't matter.

00:45:49.160 --> 00:45:50.720
All of the ideas
you come up with

00:45:50.720 --> 00:45:53.570
are probably good, good enough
to put a weekend of time

00:45:53.570 --> 00:45:54.309
into them.

00:45:54.309 --> 00:45:55.850
But until you put
that commitment in,

00:45:55.850 --> 00:45:58.130
you're never going to learn
enough about yourself.

00:45:58.130 --> 00:46:00.520
And your own true
interests, they'll

00:46:00.520 --> 00:46:02.900
just keep going
along the surface.

00:46:02.900 --> 00:46:04.724
Which could be
fine, but you have

00:46:04.724 --> 00:46:06.140
to realize that
that's really what

00:46:06.140 --> 00:46:07.806
you like to do rather
than being someone

00:46:07.806 --> 00:46:12.350
who's committed to an idea to
build it, to build something.

00:46:12.350 --> 00:46:13.190
Question?

00:46:13.190 --> 00:46:13.954
All right.

00:46:13.954 --> 00:46:16.370
AUDIENCE: So this question is
stemming from my discussions

00:46:16.370 --> 00:46:18.770
with a friend about creativity.

00:46:18.770 --> 00:46:21.260
So personally, in
my free time, I

00:46:21.260 --> 00:46:25.460
like listening to podcasts
about various things.

00:46:25.460 --> 00:46:27.380
I don't like listening
to music that much.

00:46:27.380 --> 00:46:28.850
For example, on
my way to work, I

00:46:28.850 --> 00:46:30.920
listen to audio books and stuff.

00:46:30.920 --> 00:46:33.290
And according to my
friend, keeping my brain

00:46:33.290 --> 00:46:35.710
this occupied, even
in my free time,

00:46:35.710 --> 00:46:37.910
it may be destroying
my creativity.

00:46:37.910 --> 00:46:40.220
So do you think that
has any validity?

00:46:40.220 --> 00:46:41.932
Or--

00:46:41.932 --> 00:46:43.640
SCOTT BERKUN: That
should be the podcast.

00:46:43.640 --> 00:46:45.290
Creativity destroyer.

00:46:45.290 --> 00:46:49.130
Listen to this, you will
never have an idea again.

00:46:49.130 --> 00:46:49.730
Yes and no.

00:46:49.730 --> 00:46:50.780
Everybody's different.

00:46:50.780 --> 00:46:52.580
And the way people
relax and what

00:46:52.580 --> 00:46:54.710
makes them feel
comfortable is different.

00:46:54.710 --> 00:46:56.480
So there's no universal answer.

00:46:56.480 --> 00:46:59.090
I can say though, and there
is neuroscience and cognitive

00:46:59.090 --> 00:47:04.220
psychology behind this, why
you get ideas in the shower.

00:47:04.220 --> 00:47:06.230
Who here has gotten
an idea in the shower?

00:47:06.230 --> 00:47:07.501
Who here showers?

00:47:07.501 --> 00:47:08.000
Good.

00:47:08.000 --> 00:47:08.730
All right.

00:47:08.730 --> 00:47:10.010
Excellent.

00:47:10.010 --> 00:47:12.200
What goes on there
is, the reason why

00:47:12.200 --> 00:47:13.790
it's become like
a sacred place is

00:47:13.790 --> 00:47:16.820
that it's one of the few places
where there's no screens,

00:47:16.820 --> 00:47:19.950
there's no music by default,
your body is relaxed,

00:47:19.950 --> 00:47:23.770
it's comfortable, and
your higher brain--

00:47:23.770 --> 00:47:26.170
the logical part of
your brain-- is quieter.

00:47:26.170 --> 00:47:27.490
And there's no input.

00:47:27.490 --> 00:47:30.530
So your subconscious, which
is where all the associations

00:47:30.530 --> 00:47:33.890
between things the source of
our ideas it's easier for ideas

00:47:33.890 --> 00:47:35.300
to bubble up.

00:47:35.300 --> 00:47:39.460
So as long as there's some
time regularly for you

00:47:39.460 --> 00:47:40.940
where that's true--

00:47:40.940 --> 00:47:42.860
and it could be when
you go for a walk,

00:47:42.860 --> 00:47:43.835
it could be when
you're running, it

00:47:43.835 --> 00:47:45.020
could be when you're at the gym.

00:47:45.020 --> 00:47:46.561
As long as there's
some state of mind

00:47:46.561 --> 00:47:50.514
that you reach where your
higher brain is quiet,

00:47:50.514 --> 00:47:51.680
that's when it could happen.

00:47:51.680 --> 00:47:53.600
And for some people listening
to podcasts and stuff.

00:47:53.600 --> 00:47:54.810
I listen to the
radio all the time,

00:47:54.810 --> 00:47:56.934
I listen to podcasts all
the time, even at the gym.

00:47:56.934 --> 00:47:59.410
Sometimes I'm tuned in
and sometimes it's on

00:47:59.410 --> 00:48:01.650
and my brain is somewhere else.

00:48:01.650 --> 00:48:05.270
So just the fact that that
input is there doesn't mean it

00:48:05.270 --> 00:48:07.820
doesn't necessarily define
what's going on in your brain.

00:48:07.820 --> 00:48:10.730
But there's lots of
evidence for this.

00:48:10.730 --> 00:48:12.440
Often, it's physical
activity where

00:48:12.440 --> 00:48:16.040
our higher brains are more
quiet and the subconscious

00:48:16.040 --> 00:48:16.670
can bubble up.

00:48:16.670 --> 00:48:19.340
So for some people it's
running, or going for a walk,

00:48:19.340 --> 00:48:20.650
going for a hike.

00:48:20.650 --> 00:48:23.030
So you should think
about what habit you have

00:48:23.030 --> 00:48:25.164
where your higher brain
is idle and you're not

00:48:25.164 --> 00:48:27.830
problem solving but there's some
other passive thing that you're

00:48:27.830 --> 00:48:29.780
doing that works for you.

00:48:29.780 --> 00:48:33.470
And you'll have to
experiment to find it.

00:48:33.470 --> 00:48:36.080
We have time for maybe
one or two more questions.

00:48:36.080 --> 00:48:37.502
Yes, sir?

